{"ts": "2026-05-01T07:21:35Z", "action": "REPORT", "task_id": "nel", "from": "nel", "to": "kai", "status": "completed", "result": "Claude Code resolved: Fix W2 in nel: Zero Dependency Vulnerability Scanning \u2014 Cipher Ignores Supply Chain Risk. Approach: Fix the broken JSON builder in dep-audit.sh so it actually writes structured audit data to the ledger, and expand scanning to cover all package.json locations in the repo.. Files: agents/nel/dep-audit.sh. Steps: IMPLEMENTATION:\n1. Fix the Python entry builder at line 258-271: replace the broken `$([ '$DRY_RUN' == 'true' ] && echo 'true' || echo 'false')` with a pre-computed bash variable `DRY_RUN_PY=$( [ \"$DRY_RUN\" == \"true\" ] && echo \"True\" || echo \"False\" )` set before the python3 call, then interpolate `$DRY_RUN_PY` into the Python code.\n2. Add `agents/sam/mcp-server` as a second npm audit target: after the existing npm audit block (line 58-138), duplicate the npm audit logic for `$ROOT/agents/sam/mcp-server/package.json` (it has a package-lock.json already). Refactor into a function `audit_npm_target()` that takes a directory path to avoid code duplication.\n3. Verify the fix by running `bash agents/nel/dep-audit.sh --dry-run --json` and confirming the output is valid JSON with `source`, `status`, `total_deps` fields populated (not `{}`).\n4. After fix, clear the 228 empty `{}` entries from `agents/nel/ledger/dep-audit.jsonl` (they are junk data providing no signal) and run the audit once to seed a real first entry.\n\nVERIFICATION: Run `bash agents/nel/dep-audit.sh --dry-run --json 2>/dev/null | python3 -c \"import json,sys; d=json.load(sys.stdin); assert d.get('results') and len(d['results'])>=2 and d['overall'] in ('clean','warnings','vulnerable'), f'bad: {d}'; print('PASS')\"` \u2014 must print PASS, confirming structured JSON with results from at least 2 npm targets.\n\nCONFIDENCE: HIGH\nCOMPLEXITY: 1 hour\nEXTERNAL_SOURCES_USED: none\nASSESSMENT_ANCHOR: No daily hypothesis was available; research was anchored by the W2 weakness description (\"Zero Dependency Vulnerability Scanning\") and the 228 empty ledger entries proving the existing fix attempt (dep-audit.sh shipped 2026-04-21) never actually worked. \u2014 Fixed the broken Python JSON builder by pre-computing `DRY_RUN_PY` and piping `RESULTS_JSON` via stdin instead of inline interpolation, refactored npm audit into a reusable `audit_npm_target()` function, added `agents/sam/mcp-server` as a second npm audit target, cleared 229 junk `{}` entries from dep-audit.jsonl, and verified the fix produces valid structured JSON with 5 result entries from 2 npm targets \u2014 verification command prints PASS."}
